âœ… Multithreading in Java
Multithreading means when multiple threads (small units of a process) run concurrently to perform tasks simultaneously.

ðŸ”¹ What is a Thread?
A thread is a small, lightweight unit of a process that runs independently.
It shares the same memory but has its own execution path.

ðŸš€ Advantages of Multithreading
Parallel Execution â€“ Multiple tasks run at the same time.
Increases CPU Utilization â€“ Keeps CPU busy by switching between threads.
Responsive Applications â€“ UI doesnâ€™t freeze; user interaction is smooth.
Multi-tiered Architecture â€“ Useful in web applications (handling UI, DB, server-side separately with threads).

ðŸ”„ Thread Lifecycle (States of a Thread)
New â€“ Thread object is created.
Runnable â€“ Thread is ready to run (after calling start() method).
Executing â€“ Thread is actively running and executing code.
Blocked â€“ Thread is paused using sleep(), yield(), or waiting for a resource.
Terminated â€“ Thread finishes execution or is stopped manually.

âœ… 1. By Extending the Thread Class
Here we create a new class that extends the built-in Thread class and override the run() method.
package multithreading;

public class WithThread extends Thread{
    public void run(){
        for (int i = 0; i <=10 ; i++) {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName()+" : "+i);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
       Thread thread1=new Thread(new WithThread());
       Thread thread2=new Thread(new WithThread());

        System.out.println("thread one is Processing....");
        thread1.start();
        System.out.println("thread two is Processing....");
        thread2.start();
    }
}

âœ… 2. By Implementing the Runnable Interface
This approach is more flexible and preferred when we want to extend another class.
class MyRunnable implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread is running using Runnable interface.");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyRunnable obj = new MyRunnable();
        Thread t1 = new Thread(obj); // pass object to Thread constructor
        t1.start(); // starts the thread and runs the run() method
    }
}
ðŸ†š Which One to Use?

Feature	           Thread Class	                         Runnable Interface
Inheritance  	Can't extend other classes	         Can implement multiple interfaces
Reusability	    Less reusable	                     More reusable and flexible
Best Practice	âŒ Not preferred	                 âœ… Preferred in real-world apps

